  <h2>Prince Edward Island Garden Timing Notes</h2>

  <p>
    Prince Edward Island’s climate is strongly shaped by surrounding ocean water.
    The maritime influence moderates extreme cold and heat, but it also slows spring warming
    and limits peak summer heat accumulation. Success here usually comes from steady timing
    and realistic crop expectations rather than pushing early planting dates.
  </p>

  <h3>1) Spring soil warming can lag</h3>
  <p>
    Even when air temperatures feel comfortable, soil can remain cool well into late spring.
    Warm-season crops planted too early often stall rather than gain an advantage.
  </p>
  <p class="small muted">
    If you're unsure when soil is warm enough for planting,
    <a href="/guides/best-soil-thermometer-for-gardening-in-cold-climates/">
      this guide explains why soil temperature matters in cool climates
    </a>.
  </p>

  <h3>2) Summer heat is moderate</h3>
  <p>
    PEI generally avoids extreme heat waves, but total growing degree day accumulation
    can be lower than inland continental regions. Heat-loving crops may mature more slowly.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Shorter-maturity varieties improve reliability.</strong></li>
    <li><strong>Use the sunniest, most sheltered locations for tomatoes and peppers.</strong></li>
  </ul>

  <h3>3) Coastal moderation works both ways</h3>
  <p>
    Surrounding water can delay fall frost slightly in some areas, but it also keeps
    nights cooler during the growing season. Inland low spots may frost earlier than
    exposed coastal slopes.
  </p>

  <h3>4) Wind exposure affects plant performance</h3>
  <p>
    Open coastal sites can experience persistent wind, which increases stress and
    moisture loss. Wind protection often improves both growth rate and final yield.
  </p>
  <p class="small muted">
    If your yard performs differently than regional averages,
    <a href="/guides/how-microclimates-change-frost-dates/">
      this explains how microclimates shift frost timing
    </a>.
  </p>

  <h3>How to use your numbers</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Use frost dates and remaining heat as a baseline.</li>
    <li>Favor moderate or short-maturity varieties.</li>
    <li>Add margin if you garden inland or in a low-lying site.</li>
  </ol>

  <p class="small muted" style="margin:0.5rem 0 0 0;">
    In Prince Edward Island, steady heat accumulation and realistic variety choice
    are the keys to consistent harvests.
  </p>
</section>